{"cursor":"10316","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'Nation' may refer to a community of people who share a common language,\nculture, ethnicity, descent, or history. However, it can also refer to people\nwho share a common territory and government (for example the inhabitants of a\nsovereign state) irrespective of their ethnic make-up; that is, a nation\nstate. The word nation can more specifically refer to\npeople of North American Indians. World Book Dictionary\ndefines nation as âthe people occupying the same country, united under the same\ngovernment, and usually speaking the same languageâ. Another definition is that\nnation is a âsovereign state.â It also says nation can refer to âa people, race,\nor tribe; those having the same descent, language, and history.â World Book\nDictionary also gives this definition: âa tribe of North American Indians.â\nWebsterâs New Encyclopedic Dictionary defines nation as âa community of people\ncomposed of one or more nationalities with its own territory and governmentâ and\nalso as âa tribe or federation of tribes (as of American Indians)â. Nation\ncarries varying meanings, and the connotation of the term has changed over time.\n\nAn ethnic community, or ethnie, shares a common myth of origins and descent, a\ncommon history, elements of distinctive culture, a common territorial\nassociation, and sense of group solidarity. A nation is much more impersonal,\nabstract, and overtly political than an ethnic group. It is a cultural-political\ncommunity that has become conscious of its coherence, unity, and particular\ninterests. See, Anthony D. Smith, \"Ethnie and Nation in the Modern World\",\nMillennium, 14:2 (1983), 128-32; Peter Alter, Nationalism (London: Edward\nArnold, 1989), 17.\n","linknr":377,"url":"nation","recorded":1376420554,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Nation&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Nation&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_de